Our poet accounts for the origin of systematic speech much more philosophically, and perfectly in unison with the modern theories of Buffon, lord Monboddo, and Mr. H. Tooke. Animals of every class and description, lie observes, have a natural language of their own; or, in other words, they have a power of expressing definite sensations by definite tenes: mankind, therefore, on their earliest creation, must have been possest of a species of natural language in common with animals in general.
